  "tax-invoice-australia": {
    title: "Tax Invoice Australia: GST Rules & Free Template",
    description:
      "What an Australian tax invoice must include — ABN, GST, and the words 'Tax Invoice'. Create a compliant-looking tax invoice free online.",
    date: "2026-06-03",
    updated: "2026-06-11",
    readMins: 4,
    keywords: ["tax invoice australia", "gst invoice australia", "tax invoice template", "abn invoice"],
    excerpt: "What an Australian tax invoice must show — ABN, GST, and required fields — plus a free way to create one.",
    body: [
      { type: "p", text: "A$82.50. That oddly precise number sits at the centre of Australian invoicing: once a GST-registered seller makes a taxable sale above it, the buyer is entitled to a proper tax invoice, and a casual bill won't do. If you're registered for GST, “tax invoice” isn't a fancier word for invoice. It's a specific document with required contents, and getting it right is what lets your business customers claim their GST credits without friction." },
      { type: "h2", text: "What a tax invoice must show" },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        "The words <strong>“Tax Invoice”</strong>, prominently. Not “Invoice”, not “Bill”: buyers' bookkeepers look for the phrase.",
        "Your identity: business or trading name, plus your <strong>ABN</strong>.",
        "The <strong>date</strong> the invoice was issued.",
        "A description of what was sold, with quantities where they apply.",
        "The <strong>GST amount</strong>, either as its own line or as the statement “Total price includes GST”.",
        "The <strong>total price</strong>.",
        "For sales of <strong>A$1,000 or more</strong>: the buyer's identity or ABN as well.",
      ] },
      { type: "h2", text: "Why buyers care so much" },
      { type: "p", text: "A GST-registered buyer can usually claim back the GST in your price, but only with a valid tax invoice in hand. A missing ABN or absent GST line doesn't just look sloppy; it can hold up the buyer's credit claim, which is why business customers bounce defective invoices back instead of paying them. A correct tax invoice is, quite literally, worth money to the person receiving it." },
      { type: "h2", text: "A worked example at 10%" },
      { type: "p", text: "A Brisbane electrician rewires a café's kitchen. The document reads: “Tax Invoice #2026-114. Sparks Electrical Pty Ltd, ABN 12 345 678 901. Issued 11 June 2026. Bill to: Driftwood Café Pty Ltd. Labour: 3 hrs × A$110 = A$330. Safety switch and parts: A$90. Subtotal: A$420. GST (10%): A$42. Total: A$462.” At A$462 the café's details weren't strictly required, but including them costs nothing and helps the café's bookkeeper claim the A$42 GST credit without a single follow-up question." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Showing GST: two valid styles" },
      { type: "p", text: "When everything on the invoice attracts GST, you can either show GST as a separate line (as above) or charge GST-inclusive prices and add the sentence “Total price includes GST”. Mixed invoices, where some items are GST-free, need more care: each taxable sale must be identifiable, so a proper GST breakdown is the safer habit. Whichever style you choose, use it consistently; bookkeepers process familiar layouts faster." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Not registered for GST? Different rules" },
      { type: "p", text: "If your turnover is under the registration threshold and you haven't registered, you issue regular invoices: no GST line, and crucially no “Tax Invoice” title, since that phrase belongs to GST-registered sellers. Your ABN still matters enormously, because a business paying an invoice that lacks one is generally required to withhold tax from the payment at the top rate. Our <a href=\"/blog/australia-tax-invoice-guide\">deeper guide to ATO invoice rules</a> covers registration thresholds and the no-ABN withholding trap in detail." },
      { type: "h2", text: "Five habits that keep Australian invoices clean" },
      { type: "ol", items: [
        "Put “Tax Invoice” in your template's header once, so it can never be forgotten.",
        "Show your ABN on every invoice, registered for GST or not.",
        "Number invoices sequentially and keep copies for five years.",
        "For sales of A$1,000 or more, capture the buyer's name or ABN before invoicing.",
        "For borderline items or current thresholds, check the ATO's current requirements rather than relying on a template or memory — the rules do get updated.",
      ] },
      { type: "callout", text: "Bill in Australian dollars with the GST line handled for you: the <a href=\"/invoice-generator-australia\">free Australian tax invoice generator</a> formats ABN, GST, and totals on a clean PDF." },
      { type: "p", text: "General guidance only, not tax advice — confirm the specifics with your accountant or the ATO." },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: "When does an invoice need to say “Tax Invoice”?", a: "When you're registered for GST and make a taxable sale over A$82.50 including GST, the buyer is entitled to a tax invoice bearing those words. Below that amount, or if you're not registered, a regular invoice is fine." },
      { q: "Do I have to show GST as a separate line on an Australian invoice?", a: "Not always. If everything on the invoice is taxable, you may instead state “Total price includes GST”. A separate GST line is the safer habit, and it's the clearer one whenever an invoice mixes taxable and GST-free items." },
      { q: "Can I invoice in Australia without being registered for GST?", a: "Yes. You simply issue regular invoices with no GST and without the words “Tax Invoice”. Keep your ABN on them regardless, because payments against invoices without an ABN can be subject to withholding at the top tax rate." },
      { q: "What extra details do tax invoices need for sales of A$1,000 or more?", a: "The buyer's identity or ABN must appear in addition to the standard fields. Many businesses include buyer details on every tax invoice regardless of size, which is simpler than tracking the threshold." },
    ],
  },

